  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Should my quadruplet brothers and I apply to HYS together if we aren't academically similar (test score wise)?",
  "response": "Applying to Harvard, Yale, or Stanford (HYS) together with your quadruplet brothers could be a unique and compelling story, especially if you highlight the bond and shared experiences you\u2019ve had growing up as quadruplets. However, the decision to apply together\u2014and whether it\u2019s advantageous\u2014depends on several factors, particularly given that you aren\u2019t academically similar in terms of test scores.\n\nHere are some considerations:\n\n### 1. **Individual Strengths Matter**\n   - Admissions committees evaluate applicants individually, even if you apply as a family. Your academic profile\u2014including test scores, GPA, coursework, and extracurriculars\u2014will be assessed on its own merits.\n   - If your brothers have significantly higher or lower test scores, it won\u2019t directly impact your application, but it\u2019s important to ensure each of you has a strong, well-rounded application that highlights your unique strengths.\n\n### 2. **Leverage Your Shared Story**\n   - Being quadruplets is a rare and interesting aspect of your identity that could make your applications stand out. If you choose to apply together, consider crafting essays or supplemental materials that reflect your shared experiences, collaboration, and individual growth as part of a quadruplet set.\n   - However, avoid making your quadruplet status the sole focus of your application. Admissions officers will still want to see your individual achievements, passions, and potential contributions to the university.\n\n### 3. **Fit for Each School**\n   - Make sure HYS is the right fit for each of you individually. These schools are highly selective, and you\u2019ll need to demonstrate not only academic excellence but also a strong alignment with the school\u2019s values, culture, and opportunities.\n   - If one or more of you might be a better fit for another top-tier school, it\u2019s worth considering applying to different schools to maximize your chances of acceptance.\n\n### 4. **Potential Downsides of Applying Together**\n   - Admissions officers may compare your applications more closely if you apply together, especially if you share similar extracurriculars or interests. This could highlight academic disparities if one of you has significantly stronger test scores or grades.\n   - If you\u2019re all applying in the same academic year, it could raise questions about whether you\u2019re applying because of genuine fit or simply because you want to attend the same school.\n\n### 5. **Strategize Individually**\n   - While applying together could be a compelling narrative, it\u2019s more important to focus on crafting the strongest possible application for each of you individually. This might mean choosing different schools or applying to HYS only if it\u2019s the best fit for your specific goals and profile.\n\n### 6. **Consider the \"Quirky Factor\"**\n   - Admissions officers at elite schools often look for unique stories or perspectives. Being quadruplets could work in your favor, but only if it\u2019s framed in a way that adds depth to your application rather than being a gimmick.\n\n### Final Thoughts:\nIf you and your brothers are passionate about HYS and believe each of you has a strong, well-rounded application\u2014despite differences in test scores\u2014it\u2019s worth applying. However, don\u2019t feel obligated to apply to the same schools just because you\u2019re quadruplets. Focus on finding the best fit for each of you individually, whether that\u2019s HYS or another institution.\n\nGood luck to all of you!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
